==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: passenger pigeon
<hw>passenger pigeon</hw> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <def>A once common wild
pigeon of North America (<spn>Ectopistes migratorius</spn>), now
extinct. It was so called on account of its extensive
migrations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The passenger pigeon presents a striking example of how
dramatic a negative influence man can have on other species. The
population of the passenger pigeon is estimated to have been at one time
as high as five billion in North America, but over a period of about one
hundred years large scale hunting for use as food and killing for
⟦ldquo⟧sport⟦rdquo⟧ reduced the numbers below that necessary to sustain
existence of the species. At one time over 200,000 birds were shipped to
the food markets in one day. The last wild pigeon is believed to have
died in 1900, and the last bird in captivity died in 1914. It is a rare
example of the date of a man-made extinction being recorded with
certainty.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

